```typescript
// Define the Product type alias
type Product = {
    id: number;
    name: string;
    price: number;
    inStock?: boolean;  // Optional property
};

// Create product objects
const laptop: Product = {
    id: 101,
    name: "MacBook Pro",
    price: 1999.99,
    inStock: true
};

const headphones: Product = {
    id: 102,
    name: "AirPods Pro",
    price: 249.99
    // inStock is optional, can be omitted
};

// Function using the Product type
function displayProduct(product: Product): void {
    console.log(`${product.name} - $${product.price}`);
    if (product.inStock !== undefined) {
        console.log(`In stock: ${product.inStock}`);
    }
}

displayProduct(laptop);
// Output:
// MacBook Pro - $1999.99
// In stock: true
```

The `?` makes `inStock` optional, meaning it can be present or omitted without causing errors.

**Arrays** hold multiple values of the **same type** (or union of types) with **no fixed length**:

```typescript
// Array of numbers
let scores: number[] = [85, 90, 78, 92];
scores.push(88);  // Can add more elements

// Array of strings
let names: string[] = ["Alice", "Bob"];
names.push("Charlie");
```

**Tuples** have a **fixed length** and **each position has a specific type**:

```typescript
// Tuple: [string, number]
let person: [string, number] = ["Alice", 25];

person = [25, "Alice"];  // ❌ ERROR: Wrong order
person = ["Alice", 25, true];  // ❌ ERROR: Too many elements
```

**When to use arrays:**
- List of similar items (user names, product IDs, scores)
- Length is variable and can grow/shrink
- All elements are the same type

**When to use tuples:**
- Fixed structure data (coordinates: `[x, y]`, RGB colors: `[r, g, b]`)
- Function returning multiple values of different types
- React hooks: `const [count, setCount] = useState(0);`

**Real-world examples:**

```typescript
// Array: List of temperatures (variable length)
let temperatures: number[] = [72, 68, 75, 70, 73];

// Tuple: Geographic coordinates (fixed: latitude, longitude)
let location: [number, number] = [40.7128, -74.0060];

// Tuple: Database row (id, name, active status)
let user: [number, string, boolean] = [101, "Alice", true];
```
